03:01.414 --> 03:05.317
We moved up to the South Bronx
in 1963

03:05.319 --> 03:08.754
from Greenwich village
to the South Bronx.

03:08.756 --> 03:10.722
It was a completely
different world.

03:10.724 --> 03:12.891
The buildings were beautiful,
very spacious.

03:12.893 --> 03:14.593
The blocks were wide.

03:14.595 --> 03:17.362
There were still Jews
living there at the time,

03:17.364 --> 03:20.599
pockets of Italians and Irish
still lived in the community.

03:20.601 --> 03:23.435
The South Bronx
at the time was fantastic.

03:23.437 --> 03:24.870
It was just a completely
different world.

03:24.872 --> 03:26.505
It was a world of discovery.

03:34.948 --> 03:39.851
In those days, I didn't
like the idea of joining a gang.

03:39.853 --> 03:41.720
I started my own thing.

03:41.722 --> 03:43.689
When I started
the ghetto brothers,

03:43.691 --> 03:45.891
originally it wasn't
supposed to be a gang.

03:45.893 --> 03:47.726
It wasn't supposed
to be an organization.

03:47.728 --> 03:49.228
It was a brother thing.

03:49.230 --> 03:50.996
It was basically
my brothers and I.

03:50.998 --> 03:53.465
We lived in Manhattan,
we moved to the Bronx,

03:53.467 --> 03:55.367
and those days,
it was the ghetto.

03:55.369 --> 03:57.469
So we were ghetto brothers.
Who were ghetto brothers?

03:57.471 --> 04:00.639
Robin, Benjy, Victor,
those were the ghetto brothers,

04:00.641 --> 04:02.507
my brothers, okay?

04:02.509 --> 04:05.277
Then later on,
since I knew a lot of the kids

04:05.279 --> 04:07.012
in the community,
I was very friendly,

04:07.014 --> 04:09.348
I was amicable,
everybody got along with me,

04:09.350 --> 04:11.450
so I said, you know,
let's expand this.

04:16.755 --> 04:20.559
I met Charlie at 150th St.
And trinity Avenue.

04:20.560 --> 04:22.527
I was with my friend Raymond.
He was like a brother.

04:22.529 --> 04:25.597
We grew up together,
and we saw this guy

04:25.599 --> 04:28.767
taking a wood thing
and going... bah!

04:28.769 --> 04:30.569
And breaking it. I said wow.

04:30.571 --> 04:33.372
I found that amazing because
I was into the martial arts.

04:33.374 --> 04:36.475
And I said, "that is fantastic
I wanna make friends with him."

04:36.477 --> 04:37.709
That was me.

04:37.711 --> 04:39.645
"I want to make friends
with this guy."

04:39.647 --> 04:44.316
I walk up T him, and I said,
"hi, my name is Benjy."

04:44.318 --> 04:47.686
It's 1960-something.

04:47.688 --> 04:52.624
I only know they rob,
they steal.

04:52.626 --> 04:56.695
Nobody's gonna rob me.
So I prepare.

04:56.697 --> 04:59.298
I'm ready to take this guy on.

04:59.300 --> 05:00.999
"I just want to shake
your hand."

05:01.001 --> 05:02.334
That's Charlie.

05:02.336 --> 05:03.702
I said, okay,

05:03.704 --> 05:06.638
the moment he moves,
his ass is mine.

05:06.640 --> 05:09.675
But he's standing there
with his hand out,

05:09.677 --> 05:12.678
and he starts telling me
about there's a few guys

05:12.680 --> 05:16.448
that study martial arts
that he's been watching,

05:16.450 --> 05:20.585
and he can imagine that I'm
a pretty good martial artist.

05:20.587 --> 05:22.854
"And we sat down,
he said what's your style?"

05:22.856 --> 05:24.823
I Says, "I'm Goju. Talk to me."

05:24.825 --> 05:27.092
And we just talked
and talked and talked.

05:27.094 --> 05:30.062
I stick out my hand,
I put my hand in his,

05:30.064 --> 05:35.033
and the ghetto brothers are one.

05:43.743 --> 05:46.111
<i>The '60s
were a time of worldwide</i>

05:46.113 --> 05:48.480
<i>social and cultural reckoning.</i>

05:48.482 --> 05:50.816
<i>With movements demanding change
spreading across</i>

05:50.818 --> 05:52.984
<i>the college campuses
and the front lines</i>

05:52.986 --> 05:55.053
<i>of America's ghettos,
it truly felt</i>

05:55.055 --> 05:58.523
<i>like the seeds for a full-blown
revolution were being sown.</i>

06:09.001 --> 06:11.403
So we thought this revolution
was gonna happen.

06:11.405 --> 06:13.705
We knew that this was the end
of the world order.

06:13.707 --> 06:15.974
We thought revolution
was possible.

06:15.976 --> 06:20.011
For the first time,
we had a multicultural movement.

06:20.013 --> 06:22.514
For me, it reconfirmed
in a strange way

06:22.516 --> 06:23.782
my faith in America.

06:33.493 --> 06:35.927
<i>But as the '60s came to a close,</i>

06:35.929 --> 06:37.696
<i>the Vietnam war and racism</i>

06:37.698 --> 06:39.965
<i>continue to erode America's soul</i>

06:39.967 --> 06:41.833
<i>and fade all optimism.</i>

06:41.835 --> 06:44.569
<i>A systematic backlash
against organizations</i>

06:44.571 --> 06:47.506
<i>like the black panthers
coupled with the assassinations</i>

06:47.508 --> 06:49.841
<i>of nearly every iconic figure
of hope</i>

06:49.843 --> 06:52.477
<i>left a new generation
with nothing more</i>

06:52.479 --> 06:54.012
<i>than unfocused rage.</i>

06:54.014 --> 06:55.414
They killed the king.

06:56.617 --> 06:58.683
And then they killed Kennedy.

06:58.685 --> 07:02.421
My heroes died in the '60s.

07:02.423 --> 07:04.423
The hope is deflated.

07:04.425 --> 07:06.992
I was so mad at America.
I was pissed.

07:06.994 --> 07:08.994
Heard of the troubled '60s?

07:08.996 --> 07:12.164
Well, the troubled '60s
give rise to the violent '70s.

07:15.902 --> 07:17.202
"I have a dream."

07:17.204 --> 07:19.604
No, you don't.

07:19.606 --> 07:21.473
"My people!

07:21.475 --> 07:23.909
We will overcome!"

07:23.911 --> 07:26.711
Boom, no,
you're not gonna overcome.

07:26.713 --> 07:29.080
You ain't getting nobody
out of this fucking ghetto.

07:32.919 --> 07:34.853
Remember the '60s?

07:34.855 --> 07:36.655
Hey!

07:36.657 --> 07:38.223
Peace!

07:38.225 --> 07:41.159
Now it was peace.

07:51.237 --> 07:54.973
<i>America's unrest was reflected
locally as New York City</i>

07:54.975 --> 07:58.176
<i>struggled under the weight
of its own mounting crises.</i>

07:58.178 --> 08:00.979
<i>A failed vision
of urban renewal pushed all</i>

08:00.981 --> 08:03.081
<i>but the city's wealthiest
to the brink</i>

08:03.083 --> 08:05.016
<i>and a new pessimism
and desperation</i>

08:05.018 --> 08:07.185
<i>made its home in its streets.</i>

08:07.187 --> 08:10.922
Here was this great city,
the international capital

08:10.924 --> 08:16.061
of commerce and culture
and communications and finance,

08:16.063 --> 08:20.198
and it was on its knees asking,
begging for help.

08:20.200 --> 08:22.534
The city was on the edge
of bankruptcy.

08:22.536 --> 08:25.904
All through the '70s remember,
industries were departing.

08:25.906 --> 08:27.672
Jobs were disappearing.

08:27.674 --> 08:29.808
If there was
a safety net before,

08:29.810 --> 08:32.744
the federal government
was basically not just ceasing

08:32.746 --> 08:34.546
to protect it
but cutting holes in it.

08:44.190 --> 08:47.826
<i>Despite the city's
financial troubles, in 1970,</i>

08:47.828 --> 08:50.529
<i>New York's cultural scene
was as vibrant as ever,</i>

08:50.531 --> 08:52.564
<i>construction
of the world trade center</i>

08:52.566 --> 08:54.599
<i>would soon be complete,
and the New York Knicks</i>

08:54.601 --> 08:56.535
<i>would win their first
championship.</i>

08:56.537 --> 08:58.737
<i>However, only four Miles away,</i>

08:58.739 --> 09:00.872
<i>due to reckless urban planning,</i>

09:00.874 --> 09:02.240
<i>the district of the South Bronx</i>

09:02.242 --> 09:04.009
<i>was rapidly becoming a symbol</i>

09:04.011 --> 09:06.111
<i>of urban decay around the world.</i>

09:06.113 --> 09:09.748
When we were young,
we remember Robert Moses.

09:09.750 --> 09:11.783
I remember the teacher
talked about a guy

09:11.785 --> 09:13.652
who was fixing up the area.

09:13.654 --> 09:16.087
They were saying
they were renovating the area.

09:16.089 --> 09:18.623
Buildings are being
taken out of commission.

09:18.625 --> 09:20.058
Hey, gotta go.

09:20.060 --> 09:21.626
We're gonna build
this highway over here.

09:21.628 --> 09:23.695
The cross Bronx expressway
at one time,

09:23.697 --> 09:27.265
that whole area was nothing
but houses, beautiful houses.

09:27.267 --> 09:29.167
He takes a wonderful borough

09:29.169 --> 09:31.636
that's made up of ployglot...
I mean, everybody was there,

09:31.638 --> 09:34.573
Ralph Lauren comes from there...
and he cuts across,

09:34.575 --> 09:35.907
he cuts a huge swath,

09:35.909 --> 09:37.976
literally destroying
the neighborhoods.

09:37.978 --> 09:39.578
This is amazing.

09:39.580 --> 09:40.979
I mean, It's amazingly creative

09:40.981 --> 09:43.682
even though it was also
humanly destructive

09:43.684 --> 09:46.985
that he thought the shortest
distance between two points

09:46.987 --> 09:48.987
is a line even If there
are houses

09:48.989 --> 09:51.723
and people, you know,
in the way of the line.

09:51.725 --> 09:53.992
And that's when things
started to go down.

09:53.994 --> 09:58.763
The economy, the store owners,
everybody just took off.

09:58.765 --> 10:01.099
You see a quiet white flight

10:01.101 --> 10:03.101
where everybody was migrating,
you know,

10:03.103 --> 10:07.339
from the concourse up to,
you know, Nyack, white plains.

10:07.341 --> 10:08.940
"Come on up, pops, come on up.

10:08.942 --> 10:10.742
"You can't stay down here
no more," you know?

10:10.744 --> 10:15.180
The rich move out
to their second and third homes.

10:15.182 --> 10:19.184
The middle class
is not far behind,

10:19.186 --> 10:21.653
and left will be the poor

10:21.655 --> 10:25.824
who require enormous services
and who will suffer.

10:32.865 --> 10:34.399
The South Bronx.

10:34.401 --> 10:37.802
It has all the superlatives...
highest crime,

10:37.804 --> 10:40.038
poorest people,
greatest unemployment,

10:40.040 --> 10:41.306
worst blight,

10:41.308 --> 10:43.308
and the world's record
for arson.

10:43.310 --> 10:46.111
In just 10 years,
more than 30,000 buildings

10:46.113 --> 10:48.380
have been set ablaze
and abandoned here.

10:48.382 --> 10:51.316
You got rats, bugs,
no heat, no water.

10:51.318 --> 10:53.418
It was terrible, terrible.

10:53.420 --> 10:55.887
It's like another
domino effect here.

10:55.889 --> 10:58.123
Then you see the burnings start.

10:58.125 --> 11:01.726
The landlord
wouldn't provide services,

11:01.728 --> 11:04.062
and the people had
to ultimately move out,

11:04.064 --> 11:06.197
and then the landlord
burned the building down

11:06.199 --> 11:07.899
and got the insurance.

11:07.901 --> 11:10.402
You know, having buildings
torched was the norm.

11:10.404 --> 11:13.304
The Bronx was like
a world of its own.

11:13.306 --> 11:16.975
The Bronx to us
was a whole world.

11:16.977 --> 11:18.343
Well, this morning
on our way into work,

11:18.345 --> 11:21.780
we had a report
that the police had located

11:21.782 --> 11:26.217
a carcass in the street
on 172nd and Bryant.

11:26.219 --> 11:30.021
Turned out to be a stripped
carcass of a gorilla.

11:30.023 --> 11:32.457
It was headless,
and the fur was removed,

11:32.459 --> 11:34.325
the skin was removed.

11:34.327 --> 11:36.161
South Bronx.

11:43.736 --> 11:46.438
It was just a feeling
of hopelessness.

11:46.440 --> 11:49.374
It wasn't like murder
was hidden.

11:49.376 --> 11:51.910
You know,
murder was very rampant.

11:51.912 --> 11:54.846
The number
of homicides about quadrupled

11:54.848 --> 11:58.817
from 1960 to 1971.

11:58.819 --> 12:00.218
There was crime from, like,

12:00.220 --> 12:02.353
the crooked politicians
to the crooked cops.

12:02.355 --> 12:05.490
In the early '70s, man,
crime was like...

12:05.492 --> 12:08.326
crime was like the major income
of the Bronx.

12:08.328 --> 12:12.230
There was lines of people
wrapped around the corner

12:12.232 --> 12:16.101
just waiting to buy a bundle
or a couple of bags of dope.

12:16.103 --> 12:17.736
When the cops drive up and down,

12:17.738 --> 12:20.839
it was like
a total pharmacy drugstore.

12:20.841 --> 12:23.108
When it got virulent,
people got into it.

12:23.110 --> 12:25.210
It's almost as If
they wanted to die,

12:25.212 --> 12:29.013
and so they got into heroin
because there was no dream.

12:42.895 --> 12:44.796
All this stuff was happening.

12:44.798 --> 12:47.432
It was too much
for anybody to understand,

12:47.434 --> 12:50.435
but one of the byproducts

12:50.437 --> 12:53.138
was a lot of kids out
on the street

12:53.140 --> 12:55.206
and a lot of locations
that would have been

12:55.208 --> 12:58.176
alternatives to the street
ceasing to exist.

12:58.178 --> 12:59.544
The system
had totally let us down.

12:59.546 --> 13:01.446
They let us do
what we wanted to do.

13:01.448 --> 13:03.815
We deal with
whatever we deal with.

13:03.817 --> 13:06.050
They deal with it
in their own manner.

13:06.052 --> 13:07.519
At the police department
was beating on us

13:07.521 --> 13:10.054
like they had a permission card.

13:10.056 --> 13:13.057
It was just total chaos.
There was nothing for us here.

13:13.059 --> 13:15.527
So we turned to each other
and said, you know,

13:15.529 --> 13:17.495
let's do something
for ourselves.

13:17.497 --> 13:19.164
Basically, that was it.

13:19.166 --> 13:21.232
Every gang was for themselves
back then.

13:21.234 --> 13:24.135
We had nobody looking
out for us, so it was us.

13:24.137 --> 13:26.538
It was the brotherhood,
it was the gang, and that's it.

13:37.116 --> 13:39.551
<i>Out of the rubble
and chaos of the city,</i>

13:39.553 --> 13:42.420
<i>a new breed
of outlaw street gangs arose,</i>

13:42.422 --> 13:44.889
<i>transforming the urban wasteland</i>

13:44.891 --> 13:47.392
<i>to a dark
and dangerous playground.</i>

13:47.394 --> 13:49.194
<i>Police estimated gang membership</i>

13:49.196 --> 13:52.564
<i>in the tens of thousands,
and these new outlaws</i>

13:52.566 --> 13:56.201
<i>maintained a firm grip
on New York City's streets.</i>

13:56.203 --> 13:58.570
The mentality of the gangs
that came out of the '70s

13:58.572 --> 14:00.572
was very violent.

14:00.574 --> 14:03.308
The street gangs that was
coming out in the late '60s,

14:03.310 --> 14:07.979
early '70s was more what
you could say savage and outlaw.

14:07.981 --> 14:11.049
These guys kicked you
and cursed you

14:11.051 --> 14:14.152
and spit on you
and urinated on you,

14:14.154 --> 14:18.957
and then showed you,
"this is who did it."

14:18.959 --> 14:20.992
Weren't you charged
with shooting a policeman?

14:20.994 --> 14:23.328
Yeah, last time I got busted,

14:23.330 --> 14:25.430
they told me, "we gonna catch
you one of these nights",

14:25.432 --> 14:27.632
and we're gonna kill you."
Some people would say

14:27.634 --> 14:30.101
they'd be very worried
If somebody told them that.

14:30.103 --> 14:32.270
Why don't you?

14:32.272 --> 14:35.039
Because, you know,
If I'm gonna die,

14:35.041 --> 14:37.475
you know,
let it happen now than later.

14:47.620 --> 14:49.621
It was all about power.

14:49.623 --> 14:51.322
I ain't got a pops.

14:51.324 --> 14:53.091
My moms ain't gonna
tell me what to do.

14:53.093 --> 14:54.259
I have all this anger.

14:54.261 --> 14:56.127
I'm gonna grab all these guys,

14:56.129 --> 14:57.896
and they're gonna do my bidding.

14:57.898 --> 14:59.497
So whatever I want
that lacked in my life,

14:59.499 --> 15:01.099
I'm gonna get it right now.

15:01.101 --> 15:02.934
It wasn't like you had a choice.

15:02.936 --> 15:05.637
Whatever gang ran the block,
you had to be a part of it.

15:05.639 --> 15:07.405
There was no civilians.

15:07.407 --> 15:10.108
You had to be in it
or you were a victim.

15:10.110 --> 15:12.410
On the outside looking in,
it looked really good.

15:12.412 --> 15:14.145
We're fighting all the time.

15:14.147 --> 15:16.481
We didn't take
any bullshit from anybody.

15:16.483 --> 15:19.117
We pretty much did
whatever we wanted.

15:23.289 --> 15:25.089
There was nothing
to look forward to.

15:25.091 --> 15:27.992
This was our life.
We lived for each other.

15:27.994 --> 15:30.094
We lived and died
for each other.

15:30.096 --> 15:31.663
We bled for each other.

15:31.665 --> 15:35.033
Whether you was right or wrong,
it didn't matter.

15:39.638 --> 15:41.372
In the steel and concrete jungle

15:41.374 --> 15:44.309
of the big city,
a tribal group survives,

15:44.311 --> 15:46.010
the one-percenters.

15:46.012 --> 15:49.080
These are the motorcycle freaks.

15:49.082 --> 15:51.082
They get a charge
out of spooking the citizens

15:51.084 --> 15:52.617
in a straight neighborhood.

15:52.619 --> 15:54.285
They live in a different world,

15:54.287 --> 15:57.021
in a strange cop-out world
of their own making.

15:57.023 --> 15:58.489
With a kick pedal and a boot,

15:58.491 --> 16:01.059
they work off their frustrations
on the maddened street.

16:05.297 --> 16:10.668
Everybody wanted to be the giant
that everyone's afraid of.

16:10.670 --> 16:15.106
Everybody wanted to be
the hells angel.

16:15.108 --> 16:20.645
Everybody wanted to be the guy
on the roaring machine.

16:20.647 --> 16:23.681
Real hard-core motorcycle,
you know,

16:23.683 --> 16:26.484
outlaw culture adapted
to the streets of New York.

16:26.486 --> 16:29.454
We had pretty much accepted it.

16:29.456 --> 16:31.389
Puerto Ricans in general
